@node Syntax highlighting
@chapter Syntax highlighting
@cindex font-lock
@cindex fontification
@cindex highlighting @subentry of errors
@cindex highlighting @subentry of syntax
@cindex syntax highlighting

Syntax highlighting is implemented for Dialog syntax using the
following font-lock faces:

@multitable {@samp{*} (as a prefix or in a rule)} {@code{dialog-escape-sequence-face}}
@headitem Syntax @tab Face
@item Topic @tab @code{dialog-topic-name-face}
@item Escape sequence @tab @code{dialog-escape-sequence-face}
@item Object name @tab @code{dialog-object-name-face}
@item Variable name @tab @code{dialog-variable-name-face}
@item @samp{*} (as a prefix or in a rule) @tab @code{dialog-operator-face}
@item @samp{@@} (as a prefix) @tab @code{dialog-operator-face}
@item @samp{~} (as a prefix) @tab @code{dialog-operator-face}
@item @samp{$} (in a rule) @tab @code{dialog-operator-face}
@item @samp{|} (in a rule) @tab @code{dialog-delimiter-face}
@item @samp{@{} @samp{@}} @tab @code{dialog-brace-face}
@item @samp{[} @samp{]} @tab @code{dialog-bracket-face}
@item @samp{(} @samp{)} @tab @code{dialog-paren-face}
@item Block-defining syntax @tab @code{dialog-special-block-face}
@end multitable

Block-defining syntax is any built-in syntax which has the form of a
rule and defines a logical block.  This includes the following forms:

@example dialog
(if) ... (then) ... (elseif) ... (then) ... (else) ... (endif)
(select) ... (or) ... (or) ... (stopping)
(select) ... (or) ... (or) ... (cycling)
(select) ... (or) ... (or) ... (at random)
(select) ... (or) ... (or) ... (purely at random)
(select) ... (or) ... (or) ... (then at random)
(select) ... (or) ... (or) ... (then purely at random)
(accumulate $Element) ... (into $Sum)
(collect $Element) ... (into $List)
(collect words) ... (into $List)
(determine object $Obj) ... (from words) ... (matching all of $List)
@end example

Three levels of font-lock are available for selection based on the
value of customization variable @code{font-lock-maximum-decoration}.
To improve performance and reduce visual distraction, it may be
preferable to use the second font-lock level which removes
highlighting for block-defining syntax, braces, brackets, and
parentheses.  It is relatively easy to manually re-add font-lock rules
for matching braces, brackets, or parentheses should it be required;
escaped characters are still highlighted by the second font-lock level
and so a later non-overriding match for these characters will always
be correct.

@example lisp
;; Use second level syntax-highlighting for dialog-mode and the
;; highest level which is available for all other modes.
(setq font-lock-maximum-decoration '((dialog-mode . 2) (t . t)))

;; Re-add font-lock for parentheses in dialog-mode.
(font-lock-add-keywords
 'dialog-mode '(("[()]" . dialog-paren-face)) 'append)
@end example

The additional face @code{dialog-warning-face} is used to highlight
usage of syntax which is likely incorrect.  This currently applies to
invalid escape sequences and any usage of the characters @samp{#},
@samp{$}, @samp{*}, @samp{@@}, @samp{|}, and @samp{~} in the wrong
context.


@node Indentation
@chapter Indentation
@cindex block
@cindex indent
@cindex indentation

Dialog Mode calculates the indentation level for a given line based on
existing indentation levels, the usage of braces, brackets, and
parentheses, and the use of special Dialog syntax which creates a
logical block.  The indentation behavior can be generally defined as:

@itemize @bullet
@item
If the current line has no indentation the indentation level will not
be changed.  Column 0 might be thought of as ``sticky''.
@item
The indentation level is incremented if at least one previous line has
no indentation and the current line is indented by any amount.
@item
The indentation level is incremented inside braces, brackets, and
parentheses.
@item
The indentation level is incremented for lines following special
syntax which defines a logical block.
@end itemize

There are two excepts to the above which are configured by default,
both implemented to match conventions used by the Dialog standard
library and example code:

@itemize @bullet
@item
The indentation level inside braces is not incremented when the
opening brace is not immediately followed by a white-space character.
@item
The indentation level is decremented for a line which only contains
the syntax @samp{(or)} with an optional trailing comment.
@end itemize

The default configuration uses 8 columns per level of indentation,
although the first level is taken as a special case.  The indentation
size can be configured by modifying the values of the customization
variables @code{dialog-indent-offset} and
@code{dialog-indent-initial-size}.

@defopt dialog-indent-offset
Specifies the number of columns used for indentation per block level.
@end defopt

@defopt dialog-indent-initial-size
Specifies a multiplier used for the first level of indentation.  If
working on a game where the first level of indentation is twice the
expected size, set this value to 2.
@end defopt

It is possible to enable or disable indentation inside braces,
brackets, and parentheses, by modifying the value of the customization
variable @code{dialog-indent-inside-block}, which is a regular
expression to be matched at the opening position of the block.  A
match means that the indentation level will be increased.

@defopt dialog-indent-inside-block
Specifies a regular expression which should be matched for indentation
to be increased within braces, brackets, and parentheses.  The match
is made with point before the character which opens the block.
@end defopt

Adding extra indentation for lines following special syntax such as
@samp{(if)} can be disabled by modifying the value of the
customization variable @code{dialog-indent-inside-special-syntax}.

@defopt dialog-indent-inside-special-syntax
Specifies whether lines following special block-defining syntax will
have their indentation level increased.  A non-nil value means that
additional indentation is applied.
@end defopt

To configure which lines inside a block will have indentation removed
to match the indentation level of the block-opening, modify the
customization variable @code{dialog-dedent-line}.

@defopt dialog-dedent-line
Specifies a regular expression which should match lines that will have
one level of indentation removed.  The match is made with point at the
indentation column for the line.
@end defopt

@cindex electric-indent-mode @subentry indentation
@kindex C-c TAB
If @code{electric-indent-mode} is enabled, lines will be re-indented
as newline characters are inserted.  The exception to this is when the
newline is inserted on a line which begins in column 0, in which case
the indentation will not be be modified.  This means that when writing
rule-heads the next line is assumed to be another rule-head, and when
writing a rule-body the next line is assumed to be a continuation of
that same rule body.  Adding and removing the leading white-space on
the line will effectively toggle between the two indentation
behaviors, the command @code{dialog-toggle-indent} can be used to do
this from anywhere on the line and is bound to @kbd{C-c TAB} by
default.

@defun dialog-toggle-indent
Toggle indentation on the current line.  When called from a position
which is less than or equal to the indentation column, move to the
indentation column.  The size of the inserted indentation will be
appropriate the current block level.
@end defun

