@node Code alignment
@section Code alignment
@cindex align
@cindex alignment @subentry of indentation
@cindex code alignment @subentry indentation

Dialog Mode defines support for aligning code that shares a line with
a rule-head.  These operations are performed by built-in Emacs
commands such as @code{align}, @code{align-current}, and
@code{align-entire}.  For example, when alignment is performed on the
following code:

@example dialog
(story title)Cloak of Darkness
(story author)          Linus Åkesson
(story noun)  A port of Roger Firth's reference game
@end example

the result will be similar to:

@example dialog
(story title)   Cloak of Darkness
(story author)  Linus Åkesson
(story noun)    A port of Roger Firth's reference game
@end example

@quotation Note
The @code{align} command operates on the current region as defined by
point and mark, even when the region is not considered to be active.
@end quotation

The alignment rules are defined in the customization variable
@code{dialog-align-rules-list}, with the default rules specifying that
all white-space adjustments used for alignment should align with a
tab-stop.

@defopt dialog-align-rules-list
Specifies the list of available alignment rules which will configured
in Dialog Mode buffers and available for use by alignment commands.
The rule format is the same as rules configured in the variable
@code{align-rules-list}.
@end defopt

To align indentation without considering tab-stops the default rules
may be adjusted; the following example shows how to modify the
tab-stop preference within the existing rule:

@example lisp
;; Configure alignment to ignore tab-stops.
(setf (alist-get 'tab-stop
                 (alist-get 'dialog-rule-body
                            dialog-align-rules-list))
      nil)
@end example


@node Motion commands
@chapter Motion commands
@cindex rule @subentry navigation @seealso{Imenu support}
@cindex rule @subentry selection
@cindex motion
@cindex navigation
@cindex navigation @subentry function @seealso{Outline support}
@cindex selection

Dialog Mode permits navigation around and selection of rule
definitions with commands such as @code{beginning-of-defun},
@code{end-of-defun}, and @code{mark-defun}; an Emacs @samp{defun}
broadly translates to a Dialog rule, from the beginning of the
rule-head to where the rule-body is terminated.

@kindex C-c C-n
@kindex C-c C-p
For moving by paragraph the commands @code{dialog-forward-paragraph}
and @code{dialog-backward-paragraph} are bound to @kbd{C-c C-n} and
@kbd{C-c C-p} respectively.  What is deemed to be a paragraph in this
context is configurable and tries to align with the buffer regions
which are modified when using fill commands, see @ref{Paragraphs} for
more details.

@defun dialog-forward-paragraph
Move forwards by Dialog paragraph.
@end defun

@defun dialog-backward-paragraph
Move backwards by Dialog paragraph.
@end defun

@kindex C-c C-u
An additional navigation function is also provided in the form of
@code{dialog-up-block}, which moves to the opening of the current
logical block, and is bound to @kbd{C-c C-u} by default.  When point
is moved by using @code{dialog-up-block}, the value of the
customization variable @code{dialog-block-motion-push-mark} determines
whether the mark ring is modified.

@defun dialog-up-block
Move to the opening of the current logical block.  This is typically
an opening @samp{@{} or @samp{[} character, the beginning of the
current rule, or before any special syntax such as @samp{(if)} which
opens a logical block.
@end defun

@defopt dialog-block-motion-push-mark
Determines whether block-based motion (such as by calling
@code{dialog-up-block}) will modify the mark ring.  A non-@code{nil}
value indicates that block motion commands are permitted to push the
previous location to the mark-ring when the value of point changes.
@end defopt

See also: @ref{Imenu support} and @ref{Outline support}.


@node Paragraphs
@chapter Paragraphs
@cindex paragraph
@cindex filling

Since text in a Dialog Mode buffer will tend to be a mix of regular
text and Dialog syntax, filling functions and commands such as
@code{dialog-forward-paragraph} and @code{dialog-backward-paragraph}
are configured to use additional rules to identify where a paragraph
begins and ends.  Non-comment lines will be split into paragraphs
based on:

@itemize @bullet
@item
Changes in the indentation level.
@item
Lines which are not indented.
@item
Lines which are empty or only contain white-space characters.
@item
Lines which have trailing comments.
@item
The value of the customization variable
@code{dialog-paragraph-delimiter}.
@end itemize

The default value of @code{dialog-paragraph-delimiter} is a regular
expression which will match specific lines of syntax, it is also
possible to use a custom regular expression or function.

@defopt dialog-paragraph-delimiter
Specifies the configuration of an additional paragraph delimiter which
is used to differentiate general text from Dialog syntax by closing
and re-opening a paragraph.  A string value is taken as a regular
expression.  A function value is taken as a function to call which
takes no arguments.  Regular expression matches and function calls are
made with point at the indentation column.  A value of @code{t} will
match on every non-comment line, effectively limiting the definition
of a paragraph to a single line.  A value of @code{nil} means that no
additional delimiter is used.
@end defopt

@menu
* Auto Fill support::
@end menu


@node Auto Fill support
@section Auto Fill support
@cindex Auto Fill

Dialog Mode supports the use of @code{auto-fill-mode} to automatically
wrap lines as they are typed.

When typing inside a rule-body, the fill is restricted to the current
paragraph as defined by the rules described in @ref{Paragraphs}.

When typing on a line which has no indentation and contains
non-comment syntax, the Auto Fill functionality is suppressed to
ensure that the line remains syntactically valid.


@node Imenu support
@chapter Imenu support
@cindex Imenu

Imenu provides indexing and navigation menus used to jump to points of
interest in the current buffer.

The Imenu index will contain all rule-heads and topics.  To assist in
determining which rule-head is which, if a rule-head or rule-body uses
a @samp{*} to reference the current topic the topic name will be
joined to the start of the menu entry using the string stored in the
customization variable @code{dialog-imenu-topic-separator} as a
separator.

@defopt dialog-imenu-topic-separator
Specifies the string used to join the current topic to the beginning
of an Imenu menu entry, should it be a rule which references the
current topic.
@end defopt

@cindex which-function-mode @subentry using Imenu data
For very large buffers, scanning for index entries can potentially be
slow, although automatic re-scanning may be preferable to manually
invoking the @samp{*Rescan*} option from the menu.  Consider
configuring @code{imenu-auto-rescan} and
@code{imenu-auto-rescan-maxout} to suitable values, bearing in mind
that some other Emacs features may also be using Imenu data.  If using
@code{which-function-mode}, which uses Imenu data to display the
context of the current buffer position, @code{imenu-auto-rescan}
should probably be set to @code{t} unless there is a noticeable
performance issue or no buffer changes are being made.


@node Outline support
@chapter Outline support
@cindex Outline
@cindex outline

Outline Mode is major mode intended to edit outline-format documents
with selective display.  The same functionality is also available
through alternate key-bindings using the minor mode version, enabled
by invoking @code{outline-minor-mode}.

Dialog Mode defines Outline settings by borrowing some conventions for
headings and their associated @emph{depth} from the built-in Lisp
mode.  Three types of headings are defined:

@itemize @bullet
@item
Comments created by three or more @samp{%} characters at the beginning
of a line, followed by at least one white-space character.
@item
Topics.
@item
Rule-heads.
@end itemize

The @emph{depth} of comment-based headings is determined by
subtracting 2 from the number of @samp{%} characters which were used.
For example, the following comments define Outline headings for the
first three levels:

@example dialog
%%% Level 1 heading
%%%% Level 2 heading
%%%%% Level 3 heading
@end example

The @emph{depth} of rule-head and topic based headings is not
variable; Rule-heads have the maximum possible value for their depth,
while topics have the maximum possible value minus 1, i.e. rule-heads
are folded inside topics and topics are folded inside comment-based
headings.


@node Configuring game files
@chapter Configuring game files
@cindex Configuring game files

The variable @code{dialog-game-files} specifies which file names are
relevant to the current game.  It is intended to be used as a
directory local variable to allow the file names to vary per project.

@defvar dialog-game-files
A list of strings which specifies the files relevant to the current
game.  The order of the files in the @code{dialog-game-files} list is
significant in the same way it is when compiling or manually running
the debug program.
@end defvar

A typical @samp{.dir-locals.el} file might look like this:

@example lisp
((nil . ((dialog-game-files . ("cloak.dg" "stdlib.dg")))))
@end example

Setting the value of @code{dialog-game-files} by other methods should
also work.  Taking a guess by looking for files with a @samp{.dg}
extension as the major mode is being initialized is potentially
inefficient and error prone but may be suitable for smaller projects
where the debug process is only managed from Dialog Mode buffers.  The
following example presumes that the sorted list of file names will
give the correct order once standard libraries are moved to the end of
the list:

@example lisp
(add-hook 'dialog-mode-hook
          (lambda ()
            (unless dialog-game-files
              (let ((files (directory-files
                            default-directory nil "\\.dg\\'")))
                ;; Move standard libraries to the end of the list.
                (dolist (lib '("stddebug.dg" "stdlib.dg"))
                  (when (member lib files)
                    (setq files (append (delete lib files) (list lib)))))
                (setq dialog-game-files files)))))
@end example

The game file names should be specified as relative to the current
project root as determined by @code{project}.  If the game source code
is being version controlled it is likely that no further configuration
will be required, in other cases it may be required to find another
way to identify the project root.  One way to do this is by using the
standard library file name as project root marker:

@example lisp
(with-eval-after-load 'project
  (add-to-list 'project-vc-extra-root-markers "stdlib.dg"))
@end example

If the project root cannot be determined the current working directory
is used instead.  This is likely to be less reliable and limits some
functionality to buffers which also happen to have the correct working
directory.


@node Flymake support
@chapter Flymake support
@cindex Flymake

Dialog Mode includes a Flymake back-end which is implemented by
compiling the game in the background and looking at messages generated
by the Dialog compiler.  The customization variable
@code{dialog-compiler-program} specifies how to find the compiler.

@defopt dialog-compiler-program
Specifies the name of the Dialog compiler executable, either a name to
be located somewhere on PATH or an absolute path to the file name.
@end defopt

Compilation runs using the original source files, as determined by
@code{dialog-game-files} (see @ref{Configuring game files}), and
because of this Dialog Mode buffers default the value of
@code{flymake-no-changes-timeout} to @code{nil} to avoid needlessly
running the compiler as the buffer is being edited.


@node Xref support
@chapter Xref support
@cindex Xref

Dialog Mode supports @emph{definition} and @emph{reference} look-ups
by pattern-matching the text which makes up a rule or query.  A
look-up for @emph{definitions} will return all successful
pattern-matches for syntax in a rule-head.  A look-up for
@emph{references} will return all successful pattern-matches for
syntax regardless of how that syntax is indented.

Pattern matches are made against the text that remains once all
numbers, objects, variables, dictionary words, and references to the
current topic have been removed.  Exceptions are made for the
declarations of interfaces and global variables, in which case the
inner-syntax form is used in-place of the syntax which appears at the
top level of the declaration.  For example, the following lines will
all successfully pattern-match with each other:

@example dialog
(increase score by 1)
(increase score by $Delta)
(interface (increase score by $<Delta))
@end example

The identifier for the lookup is the entirety of the syntax which
makes up a rule or query, with white-space collapsed down to a single
space character, and with comments removed.

To locate the usage of specific names within the identifier, such as
any rules or queries which include specific object names, it is
recommended to search within the identifiers of all @emph{references}
by using the command @code{xref-find-apropos} and entering a regular
expression.

@quotation
Note: Xref functionality does not depend on any external programs to
search for matches; searches are made by opening and searching the
original source files of the current game, as determined by
@code{dialog-game-files} (see @ref{Configuring game files}).  When a
search is initiated, any source files which are not currently open
will be opened and will remain open after the searches have ended.
@end quotation


@node Interactive debugger
@chapter Interactive debugger
@cindex debugging
@cindex interactive @subentry debugging
@cindex running the game @subentry debugging

Dialog includes a debug program which is designed to run a game in an
environment where its state can be inspected and modified.  Dialog
Mode includes support for running the debug program as a command
interpreter, meaning that:

@itemize @bullet
@item
A game can be run directly in an Emacs buffer.
@item
For any purpose, commands can be sent by Emacs to update a running
game's state.
@item
For any purpose, debug output can be intercepted by Emacs.
@end itemize

The debug program will be started with the game files specified by the
value of the variable @code{dialog-game-files}, see @ref{Configuring
game files}.

@kindex C-c C-z
The command @code{dialog-debug-run}, bound to @kbd{C-c C-z} by
default, is used to start the debug program named by the customization
variable @code{dialog-debug-program} using the current game files and
switch to the debug buffer.  The same command is also used to switch
to an existing debug buffer.  If no game files are configured or
@code{dialog-debug-run} was called with a prefix argument, a prompt
will appear to select the game files.  With a double prefix argument
the game directory can also be selected.

@quotation Note
The prompt for game files is a prompt to select multiple files, where
the completion interface will likely expect that commas are used to
separate each selected file.  The files selected at the prompt are not
stored in any way; the intended purpose of the prompts is to
temporarily override the current settings rather than initialize them.
@end quotation

@defopt dialog-debug-program
Specifies the name of the Dialog debugger executable, either a name to
be located somewhere on PATH or an absolute path to the file name.
@end defopt

@defun dialog-debug-run
Start the debug program as a command interpreter process, display its
buffer, and switch to that buffer.  If the process already exists,
just display and switch to buffer which is associated with that
process.  When called with a single prefix argument, always prompt for
the game files.  When called with a double prefix argument, always
prompt for the game directory and the game files.
@end defun

@kindex C-c C-b
To display an existing debug buffer without switching to it, the
separate command @code{dialog-debug-display-buffer} is available and
bound to @kbd{C-c C-b} by default.

@defun dialog-debug-display-buffer
Display an existing debug buffer.
@end defun

See @ref{The debug buffer} for details on how the ``current'' debug
buffer and process is determined.

