@node Sending commands
@section Sending commands
@cindex sending commands @subentry when debugging

@kindex C-c C-c
Once the Dialog debugger has been started it is possible to send debug
commands (either input for the game or debugger specific syntax) to
the debug program as if they had been manually typed at a terminal.
The command @code{dialog-debug-send-command} can be used to send a
debug command, either the default command as defined by the
customization variable @code{dialog-debug-send-command-default}, or by
prompting for a command to send if called with a prefix argument.

@defun dialog-debug-send-command
With a prefix argument, prompt for text to send as a command to the
current debug process, otherwise send the value of
@code{dialog-debug-send-command-default}.
@end defun

@defopt dialog-debug-send-command-default
Specifies the default command to the send to the debug program.
@end defopt

When using the prompt to send a debug command, a list of preset
commands is made available to the completion interface which will
handle the prompt.  The value of
@code{dialog-debug-send-command-default} determines whether the
command entered at the prompt will become the new default command.  To
update the default command directly using a similar prompt, use
@code{dialog-debug-set-default-command}.

@defopt dialog-debug-send-command-prompt-sets-default
Determines whether the command most recently specified at the prompt
will become the new default command by updating the value of
@code{dialog-debug-send-command-default}.
@end defopt

@defun dialog-debug-set-default-command
Prompt for a command which will become the new default command by
setting the value of @code{dialog-debug-send-command-default}.
@end defun

The list of preset commands and their descriptions may be edited or
entirely replaced by changing the value of the customization variable
@code{dialog-debug-send-command-presets}.

@defopt dialog-debug-send-command-presets
An alist of commands which should be valid to send to the debug
program and their descriptions.  Commands present in this list will be
suggested during command completion and are also made available to
send using menus.
@end defopt

@kindex C-c C-e
It is also possible to send debug commands represented by lines of
text in Dialog Mode buffers, using the commands
@code{dialog-debug-send-command-from-line},
@code{dialog-debug-send-command-from-region}, and
@code{dialog-debug-send-command-dwim}, the last of which is bound to
@kbd{C-c C-e} by default.

@defun dialog-debug-send-command-from-line
Send the current line as a debug command.
@end defun

@defun dialog-debug-send-command-from-region
Send the lines from the currently active region as debug commands.
@end defun

@defun dialog-debug-send-command-dwim
If there is an active region, send the lines from it as debug
commands, otherwise send the current line as a debug command.
@end defun

In all cases any leading comment syntax is removed from lines before
sending them as commands.  This allows test input to stored in the
game's source files, for example:

@example dialog
%% west
%% hang cloak on hook
%% east
%% south
%% look at message
@end example

The customization variable @code{dialog-debug-send-command-hook} is a
list of functions to call before the command is sent, at which time
the current command to send is stored in the variable
@code{dialog-debug-send-command-input}.

@defopt dialog-debug-send-command-hook
A hook which is called before sending a debug command.
@end defopt

@defvar dialog-debug-send-command-input
Stores the current debug command being sent to the debug program.
@end defvar

@cindex command hooks @subentry for debugging
@cindex hot-reload @subentry when debugging
One interesting feature of the Dialog debug program is that, if game
source files are modified while the debug program is running, the
files are reloaded and any changes are incorporated into the game
state.  The default value of @code{dialog-debug-send-command-hook}
will cause a prompt to save any unsaved buffers, but the following
example shows how to further streamline the process by automatically
saving the current Dialog Mode buffer when the debug command being
sent is @samp{@@replay}.  This makes sending the @samp{@@replay}
command an equivalent of hot-reload for incorporating the latest
buffer changes:

@example lisp
(add-hook 'dialog-debug-send-command-hook
          (lambda ()
            (when (and (derived-mode-p 'dialog-mode)
                       (equal dialog-debug-send-command-input "@@replay"))
              (save-buffer))))
@end example


@node The debug buffer
@section The debug buffer
@cindex the debug buffer @subentry debugging
@cindex determining the current debug buffer @subentry when debugging

@findex dialog-debug-mode
@kindex C-c C-c
@kindex C-c C-z
The buffer which runs the debug process will use
@code{dialog-debug-mode} as its major mode.  The majority of the
default @code{comint} key-bindings are still present in this mode,
with the exception of @kbd{C-c C-c} which is bound to
@code{dialog-debug-send-command} (see @ref{Sending commands}) and
@kbd{C-c C-z} which is bound to @code{quit-window}.

With the exception of when @code{dialog-debug-send-command} is called
directly from the debug buffer, any functionality which needs to refer
to the current debug buffer or running debug process will do so by
looking for the buffer name specified in the customization variable
@code{dialog-debug-buffer-name}.

@defopt dialog-debug-buffer-name
Specifies the name to use when creating or looking for the Dialog
debug buffer.
@end defopt

Renaming an existing debug buffer will effectively ``detach'' it from
functions which are looking to use it, allowing a new debug buffer to
be created in its place.


@node Disabling the command interpreter
@section Disabling the command interpreter
@cindex disabling the command interpreter @subentry when debugging

To run the debug program directly instead of as a command interpreter,
set the value @code{dialog-debug-as-interp} to @code{nil}.  This
reduces the functionality of the command @code{dialog-debug-run} to a
convenient way to launch an external program.

@defopt dialog-debug-as-interp
Specifies whether the debug program runs as a command interpreter.  A
non-@code{nil} value will start the debug program as a command
interpreter, which enables interactive debugging and sending commands
to the game as it is running.  A value of @code{nil} means that the
process is launched directly with no further process interaction,
which probably only makes sense if the debug program is a graphical
application.
@end defopt

@cindex Windows support @subentry for debugging
@cindex AutoHotkey @subentry for debugging
Dialog provides two debug programs for use on Microsoft Windows;
@command{dgdebug} is the Windows build of the debugger designed for
use in a terminal, while @command{dgdebug_gui} is an alternative build
which runs in a graphical window.  If using the graphical debugger,
the value of @code{dialog-debug-as-interp} should be set to nil.
Switching to the graphical debugger means that there is no direct
method for Emacs to send debug commands to the debugger.  It is still
possible to send commands indirectly by configuring the value of the
customization variable @code{dialog-debug-send-command-function} to a
suitable function.

@defopt dialog-debug-send-command-function
Specifies the function which will be used to send a debug command to
the debug program.  At the time that the function is called the value
to be sent is stored in the variable
@code{dialog-debug-send-command-input}.
@end defopt

As an example of custom configuration, the following example shows how
to switch to the graphical version of the Windows debug program and
how to send commands to it using AutoHotkey (available at
@url{https://www.autohotkey.com/}):

@example lisp
(defconst dialog-debug-send-ahk-script
  "
command := EnvGet('DIALOG_DEBUG_COMMAND')
SetTitleMatchMode 3  ; Exact match for window title.
Try @{
    ControlSend command '@{Enter@}',, 'Dialog Interactive Debugger'
@}
Catch @{
    Exit 1
@}
"
  "The AutoHotkey send command script.")

(defun dialog-debug-send-command-with-ahk ()
  "Send a command to the debug program window using AutoHotkey."
  (let ((process-environment
         (cons
          (concat "DIALOG_DEBUG_COMMAND=" dialog-debug-send-command-input)
          process-environment)))
    (message "Sending command '%s' using AutoHotkey"
             dialog-debug-send-command-input)
    (unless (eq 0 (with-temp-buffer
                    (insert dialog-debug-send-ahk-script)
                    (call-process-region (point-min) (point-max)
                                         "autohotkey" nil nil nil "*")))
      (message "Failed to send command"))))

(setq dialog-debug-program "dgdebug_gui")
(setq dialog-debug-as-interp nil)
(setq dialog-debug-send-command-function
      #'dialog-debug-send-command-with-ahk)
@end example


@node Using a pseudo-terminal
@section Using a pseudo-terminal
@cindex pseudo-terminal
@cindex using a pseudo-terminal @subentry when debugging

To make the debug process work more like it does in a regular
terminal, the value of @code{dialog-debug-use-pty} should be set to
@code{t}, which is the recommended and default value.  The main
benefits of using a pseudo-terminal are that the text output supports
styling and will be automatically wrapped to the Emacs window size
instead of assuming a fixed width.  Setting
@code{dialog-debug-use-pty} to nil may be useful to completely avoid
output paging.

@defopt dialog-debug-use-pty
Specifies whether the debug process runs using a pseudo-terminal.  A
value of @code{nil} indicates to use pipes instead of a
pseudo-terminal.  A value of @code{t} indicates to use a
pseudo-terminal.  Note that the debug buffer needs to be recreated for
changes to this variable to take effect.
@end defopt

@cindex dismissing debugger prompts @subentry when debugging
@findex dialog-debug-auto-response-mode
The minor mode @code{dialog-debug-auto-response-mode} can be enabled
in @code{dialog-debug-mode} buffers to switch on automatic responses
to game output.  This is useful when using a pseudo-terminal because
debug output is potentially paged based on the debug buffer's current
window dimensions and the length of the output.
@code{dialog-debug-auto-response-mode} will automatically dismiss any
@samp{[more]} prompts which appear.


@node Dismissing game prompts
@section Dismissing game prompts
@cindex dismissing game prompts @subentry when debugging

Any prompts which originate from the standard library are expected to
be handled by Dialog debug extensions which are loaded during game
development.  For example, to skip any ``yes/no'' prompts without
waiting for input, define a new rule for the @samp{(yesno)} predicate
which always succeeds:

@example dialog
(yesno)  %% Automatically accept yes/no prompts.
@end example


@node Viewing game state information
@section Viewing game state information
@cindex game state information
@cindex viewing game state information @subentry when debugging

@findex dialog-debug-auto-command-mode
When a game is running in the debug buffer, it is possible to
automatically send additional commands every time that a new prompt
for game input appears.  The minor mode
@code{dialog-debug-auto-command-mode} is enabled by default in debug
buffers and is pre-configured to send the commands @samp{@@dynamic}
and @samp{@@tree}.  The command and command output will not be
displayed in the debug buffer, instead being inserted into the buffer
which is stored in the buffer-local variable
@code{dialog-debug-auto-command-buffer}.  The customization variables
@code{dialog-debug-auto-command-hook} and
@code{dialog-debug-auto-command-setup-hook} can be used to act on
command output and are pre-configured to generate additional buffers
which represents game state information.

@defvar dialog-debug-auto-command-buffer
The buffer stored in this variable contains the command and output
from a command which was automatically sent.
@end defvar

@defopt dialog-debug-auto-command-hook
Functions added to this hook are called when the game prompt reappears
after automatically sending a command.
@end defopt

@defopt dialog-debug-auto-command-setup-hook
Functions added to this hook are called when the game prompt appears
before any commands are automatically sent.
@end defopt

@findex dialog-data-mode
@kindex C-c C-d d
@kindex C-c C-d t
If using the pre-configured hook values, two buffers containing game
state information will be created or updated every time that the
prompt for input reappears.  Both of these buffers use the major mode
@code{dialog-data-mode} and are named with a buffer name that is
derived from the current debug buffer name.  The commands
@code{dialog-data-display-dynamic} and @code{dialog-data-display-tree}
will display these buffers and have the key-bindings @kbd{C-c C-d d}
and @kbd{C-c C-d t} respectively in @code{dialog-mode} and
@code{dialog-debug-mode} buffers.  It is presumed that any specific
requirements around how or where @code{dialog-data-mode} buffers
should be displayed will have been handled through the configuration
of @code{display-buffer-alist} (see @ref{Example configuration}).

@defun dialog-data-display-dynamic
Display the buffer which contains data derived from the
@samp{@@dynamic} command for the current debug buffer.
@end defun

@defun dialog-data-display-tree
Display the buffer which contains data derived from the @samp{@@tree}
command for the current debug buffer.
@end defun


@node Trace output
@section Trace output
@cindex trace
@cindex tracing
@cindex following @subentry trace output

Two minor modes are defined which are intended to operate in buffers
which contain trace output, as produced by the Dialog debugger.  This
includes enabling the minor modes directly in @code{dialog-debug-mode}
buffers, where new trace output is generated in response to game
actions and debug queries.

@findex dialog-trace-mode
The minor mode @code{dialog-trace-mode} is enabled in
@code{dialog-debug-mode} buffers by default.  When enabled it
propertizes the text of Dialog trace output in order to:

@itemize @bullet
@item
Fontify the leading call depth indicators and the trailing source file
reference to make them visually distinct from the rest of the line.
@item
Turn the source file reference into a button which is highlighted by
the mouse cursor.  Activating the button will open the given file,
switch to its buffer, and move point to the relevant line.
@item
Configure the entire line of trace output to be highlighted when point
is anywhere inside the trace output and
@code{cursor-face-highlight-mode} is enabled.
@item
Assign the keymap @code{dialog-trace-map} which will be active when
point is anywhere on the trace line.
@end itemize

@quotation Note
Although this functionality is not dependent on any other specific
modes, identifying the source file links in trace output does require
that the value of @code{dialog-game-files} is set correctly (see
@ref{Configuring game files}).
@end quotation

With @code{@code{dialog-trace-mode}} enabled, the following commands
have key-bindings when point is anywhere on the trace line:

@multitable {@kbd{RET}} {@code{dialog-trace-display-file-ref}}
@headitem Key-binding @tab Command
@kindex RET
@item @kbd{RET} @tab @code{dialog-trace-pop-to-file-ref}
@kindex o
@item @kbd{o} @tab @code{dialog-trace-display-file-ref}
@kindex n
@item @kbd{n} @tab @code{dialog-trace-forward}
@kindex p
@item @kbd{p} @tab @code{dialog-trace-backward}
@kindex f
@item @kbd{f} @tab @code{dialog-trace-follow-mode}
@end multitable

@vindex dialog-trace-display-buffer-action
@defun dialog-trace-display-file-ref
Switch to the buffer and move to the line number of the file which is
referenced in the trace line at point.  The file will be opened if not
already open.  The customization variable
@code{dialog-trace-display-buffer-action} defines how and where the
buffer should be displayed.
@end defun

@vindex dialog-trace-pop-to-buffer-action
@defun dialog-trace-pop-to-file-ref
Display the buffer and move within the window to the line number of
the file which is referenced in the trace line at point.  The
displayed buffer is not selected.  The file will be opened if not
already open.  The customization variable
@code{dialog-trace-pop-to-buffer-action} defines how and where the
buffer should be displayed.
@end defun

@defun dialog-trace-forward
Move forwards to the end of the next region of trace output.
@end defun

@defun dialog-trace-backward
Move backwards to the start of the previous region of trace output.
@end defun

@findex dialog-trace-follow-mode
The minor mode @code{dialog-trace-follow-mode} enables functionality
which displays source files when trace motions commands such as
@code{dialog-trace-forward} and @code{dialog-trace-backward} are used,
automatically calling @code{dialog-trace-display-file-ref} when moving
between trace lines.  For this feature to work it is required that
@code{dialog-trace-mode} also be enabled.  The customization variable
@code{dialog-trace-follow-restore-window-configuration} determines
whether the window configuration is modified when
@code{dialog-trace-follow-mode} is disabled.

@defopt dialog-trace-follow-restore-window-configuration
Specifies whether the window configuration which was current when
@code{dialog-trace-follow-mode} was enabled should be reapplied when
the mode is disabled.  A non-nil value indicates that the window
configuration should be applied.
@end defopt

When combined with the standard minor mode hook, restoring the window
configuration provides a straight-forward way to temporarily use the
full frame while @code{dialog-trace-follow-mode} is enabled:

@example lisp
;; Configure `dialog-trace-follow-mode' to delete other windows when
;; enabled and restore the original window configuration when
;; disabled.
(setq dialog-trace-follow-restore-window-configuration t)
(add-hook 'dialog-trace-follow-mode-hook
          (lambda ()
            (when dialog-trace-follow-mode
              (delete-other-windows))))
@end example

To highlight lines or recenter buffers as source files are shown, the
customization variables @code{dialog-trace-display-file-ref-hook} and
@code{dialog-trace-pop-to-file-ref-hook} define hooks which are run by
@code{dialog-trace-display-file-ref} and
@code{dialog-trace-pop-to-file-ref} respectively.

@defopt dialog-trace-display-file-ref-hook
A hook which is run after displaying a trace file reference.
@end defopt

@defopt dialog-trace-pop-to-file-ref-hook
A hook which is run after popping to a trace file reference.
@end defopt


@node Browsing the Dialog manual
@chapter Browsing the Dialog manual
@cindex manual
@cindex browsing @subentry the manual

The command @code{dialog-browse-manual} will open the online version
of the Dialog manual, the URL for which is determined by the
customization variable @code{dialog-manual-url}.

@defun dialog-browse-manual
Open the Dialog manual in the default web-browser.  When called with a
prefix argument use the secondary browser instead of the default one.
@end defun

@defopt dialog-manual-url
Specifies the URL for the Dialog manual.
@end defopt

To open the manual using a different browser configure the value of
@code{browse-url-handlers}; if configured to open via
@code{eww-browse-url} it may be preferable to also configure the value
of @code{eww-readable-urls} so that only the main text for each page
will be displayed.


